mutant: m009_checksum_range_off_by_one
target: segment/header.go
failure-mode: |
  The header/footer checksum is computed over headerBytes[13:] instead of
  [12:], excluding one byte from the digest. The shift is SYMMETRIC: seal
  and Reader.Open share xxh3HeaderFooter, so every file the mutated build
  writes verifies cleanly under the mutated reader. Nothing inside the
  process ever disagrees — but every segment written is checksum-corrupt
  for any correct build that later opens it (rolling upgrade, downgrade,
  external tooling). Models an off-by-one in a checksum byte range.
expected-detection: |
  Corpus tier. The oracle's write-then-read-back loop structurally cannot
  see a symmetric shift (SURVIVED baseline, analyzed in RESULTS.md and
  #32). internal/corpus breaks the symmetry with committed facts from a
  known-good build: TestCorpusSegmentGolden fails on the write side (the
  sealed bytes differ from the golden file) AND on the read side (the
  committed golden's stored checksum no longer matches the mutated
  reader's digest).
expected-tier: corpus
tiers: default,stress,corpus

diff --git a/segment/header.go b/segment/header.go
index b3e6cee..5f5ece0 100644
--- a/segment/header.go
+++ b/segment/header.go
@@ -132,7 +132,7 @@ func ReadSealedHeader(r io.ReaderAt) (Header, error) {
 // finalized header.
 func xxh3HeaderFooter(headerBytes, footerBytes []byte) uint64 {
 	h := xxh3.New()
-	_, _ = h.Write(headerBytes[12:])
+	_, _ = h.Write(headerBytes[13:])
 	_, _ = h.Write(footerBytes)
 	return h.Sum64()
 }
